TITLE: Passing References as Function Arguments in V
DESCRIPTION: Shows how references are passed to functions in V with the lifetime remaining in the caller's scope. The compiler can determine that objects can be stack-allocated because references are only borrowed.
SOURCE: https://github.com/vlang/v/blob/master/doc/docs.md#2025-04-21_snippet_138

LANGUAGE: v
CODE:
```
struct MyStruct {
mut:
	n int
}

fn main() {
	mut q := MyStruct{
		n: 7
	}
	w := MyStruct{
		n: 13
	}
	x := q.f(&w) // references of `q` and `w` are passed
	println('q: ${q}\nx: ${x}')
}

fn (mut a MyStruct) f(b &MyStruct) int {
	a.n += b.n
	x := a.n * b.n
	return x
}
```

